Visual Exploration of Data - Assignment 1¶

You find yourself working as newly-hired intern for the United States Transportation Security Administration, (TSA). You receive communications from management indicating that various other stakeholders have expressed interest in data regardings claims filed with the agency. In particular, they express interest in learning more about the distribution of settlement-closure costs, and request that you produce a notebook with visualizations that can lead discussions about processing claims in a forthcoming meeting.

Elements requested by staff include:

  • Violin plots comparing the distribution of settlement/closure amounts based on "Disposition" in 2014 (excluding those that were "denied") (claims-2014.csv dataset).
  • A bar plot depicting the total settlement cost of each month in 2014 (based on the Incident Date) (claims-2014.csv dataset).
  • Boxplots comparming settlement/closure amounts of the airports that incurred the highest settlement totals in 2015 (claims-2015.csv dataset). Be conscious of the amount of airports you are choosing to visualize.
  • An appropriate visualization / plotting method of your choice that compares the total number of claims occurring in each month of 2015 to the total number of claims occurring in each month in 2014 (both datasets).
  • A justification regarding why your visualization / plotting method appropriately compares the total number of claims occurring in each month of 2015 to the total number of claims occurring in each month in 2014.

Side Note: This data, as well as comparable data for other years, can be obtained from the TSA website: here.

The files bundled with this assignment are converted to CSV for your convenience and have been slightly cleaned.</i>

Some Key Features of our data:

  • Claim Number:   unique id comprised of a date and a random 5 digit number afterwards
  • Date Received:   the date the actual claim was received
  • Incident Date:   the date the incident allegedly occurred
  • Airport Code:   the three letter acryonym for the actual airport where incident occurred
  • Airline Name:   the airline (example American Airlines, etc) that the flight was booked thru
  • Close Amount:   the amount of money that the Airline settled with the claim for
  • Disposition:   the official end state settlement status

Notes:

  • Datasets are not precisely in the same order/format/value

#Creating a helper function 

def unique_counter(your_df):
    unique_counts = pd.DataFrame.from_records([(col, your_df[col].nunique()) for col in your_df.columns],
                                              columns=['Column_Name', 'Num_Unique']).sort_values(by=['Num_Unique'])
    
    #Print out the actual table of unique value counts
    print("\n=== Unique entry counts per dataframe columns ===\n")
    print(unique_counts.to_string(index=False))  
    print("")
    
unique_counter(df_p1)

def strip_all_whitespaces_from_my_dataframe(your_dataframe):
    
    """
    Enter your dataframe, and will return a new dataframe with whitespaces removed from all
    columns (but of course will not modify any integer or float type columns)
    
    Ex:  new_df = remove_all_whitespaces_from_my_dataframe(df)
    """
    
    import numpy as np
    import pandas as pd 
    cleaned_dataframe = your_dataframe.apply(lambda x: x.str.strip() if x.dtype == "object" else x)
    return(cleaned_dataframe)

df3 = strip_all_whitespaces_from_my_dataframe(df_p3)

Final Writeup:¶

  • This visualization showed both 2014 and 2015 data standalone, as well as them on a combined bar chart, which I believe was the cleanest most visually understandable manner.
  • This approach also provided the ability to clearly see the closeness of the values per month, it is a perfect way to visualize.
  • What we see is that in 2015, the settlement costs went up (month by month), as shown in orange (versus the blue 2014 data).
Tom's Overall Comments: * There is a clear trend here: 2015 had higher settlements * Also, March and January were the two highest settlement months... * Throughout this notebook you can see the seaborn plots I have used.
